{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_greenville_ver01/data/sn95047217/00529042292/1946050901/0104.xml":{"full_text":"Page Four\nNationally-Known Leaders to Address\nGreat AFL Southern Labor Conference\nAsheville, North Carolina, May 11-12\nATLANTA Outstanding lead\nen of the American Federation of\nLabor including mo a t of the Exe\ncutive Council and International\nPresidents, will be on hand at\nAzhet lie, N C., Saturday and\nSunday i May 11 and 12) for the\nThird Biennial Southern Labor\ncon ferenc<\u00bb\nThe conference will, be by far\nthe moot important ever held in\nthe South on behalf of labor. Ila\npurposes and achk-emenU *iH\nnot only affect ever} member of\nthe American Federal.on of Labor\nbut t will be equally important\nto every wage earner in the South.\nThe program, a.- nounced by\nueorge Googe, Southern Repre-\n-muuve of the Am< roan Federa\nf labor, although abject to\n.e, would indicate that every\ninvolving ne future of\nSouthern labor will be thoroughly\nd iu^ed and a formal plan of\nnote speeches will be given\ny President William Green, Sec\nTreasurer George Meany,\nI- r tor of Organization Frank P.\nFvision and Executive Council\ni residents W Ilium Hutcheson\nd John L. Le\u00bbr\nOthers listed a, ^peakers are the\nHo Ai ayne Mor r. United States\nSii.ator from Or<. -n, former vice\nra.tman of the National War La-\nBoard; Hon Wilaon Wyatt,\ni >ma r mayor of 1 ouisville, chair\n.\u00bbi! of the National Housing com-\n0: Hon Rai,a. McGill, editor\nI >f the ABar.ta Constitu\nd Gerald P Re.Hy, senior\n-of the N r ul. mai Labor Re\nlation board\niKH ai dfoes of the American Fed\neration of Labor L ted are John I\nFrey president of the Metal I\nTrade department; 1. N Omburn,\nsecretary of the Union Label de\nart me nt; Nelson H Cruik^hank,\nMichael Widman, c retury of I\nOrganization for District 50, Unit-\npd Mine?' orxers of Americ<i wilt\nIne conference will be .veil ad-\u0964\nlu broadcast to the entire\ninto The Columb a chain will\n7. '\"77\nA mem a program Speak\nlound tabic discussion\nModerator Phillip Pearl,\nt. chosen at the\ni- :-r t i\\ t Green\u2019s prin-\n-a given on Sat-\n\u0964a p m. over the I\nBroadcasting\ni i s o\u2019clock with\nd< iegate.- and\nr. f ud^ It will\nat 10 o'clock\nA.O; ;L --c .ddress by James\ni There will be\n.dd;\u00ab one by Major\nI i..m. i -a. or of Asheville;\ni \u2018A >ident of the\ni ommerce, and\ni dent of North\nFederation of La-\nI I\" I\nPOLLERT S AILAPaTTAH\nBAKERY\nFk\u00bb place to order that Birthday\ncr Cake.\n4 N A J6th St Dial 3-2260\nr-\u25a0\nfat yom\nSears.hoebuck^ Co.\nuscAYnt &ouLfcVAM> at aw st.\nA COMPLETE DEPABTM&DT STORE\nBy om overwhelming vote in the\npi Hilary election 1 (Jnd it difficult to\nadequately express my appreciation\nha vour confidence in returning me\nto i epi esent you in Tallahassee, so\nto one and all I say\nThanks!\nRichard (Chubby) Oelkers\n<P4 Pci Adv\nbor. The opening invocation will\nbe by the Rev. Arthur W. Farnum,\nrector of St. Mary\u2019s Church and\nchaplain of the Central Labor\nUnion for the last 15 years.\nDr. Ellis Fuller, president of\nthe Southern Baptist Theological\nSeminary at Louisville, Ky., will\ndeliver the devotional sermon at\nthe opening of the Sunday morning\nNasion. In addition there will be\nGospel singing by the Gospel Sing\ners from the Birmingham Laundry\nWorkers Local union.\nNew Plan to Speed\nBuilding Industry\nPay Adjustments\nWASHINGTON, D. C. Ap\npointed full-time chairman of the\nWage Adjustment Board, Arthur\nD. Hill, Jr., former assistant soli\ncitor of the U. S. Department of\nLabor, announced a new proce\ndure for filing applications for\nwage adjustments in the building\nindustry which will permit faster\nprocessing and eliminate tempor\nary wage inequities.\nUnder the new program labor\nunions and contractors will endea\nvor to submit to the board simul\ntaneously or within a reasonable\ninterval of t ine all applications\npertaining to each craft and labor\nia.->sification for which adjust\nments are considered warranted in\na single area.\n\u201cSince many contractors submit\napplications jointly with a number\nof different union.- in an area,\u201d\nHill said, \u201ccoordination of the ap\nplications in the matter of submis\njon to the board is believed to be\nm no way burdensome or difficult\nof achievement. The local building\ntrades councils and contracting as\nociationa, which are frequently\nactive in fostering all of the appli\nations which come from a single\n.rea are particularly urged to co\noperate in securing compliance\nwith the new procedure.\u201d\nThe new program is the result\nf action by the entire board, pub\nindustry and labor members.\nThe board also feels,\u201d Hill added,\nthat the parties should specify a\ndefinite period during which agree\nment, if approved, will be in ef\nfect, and strongly urges that such\nagreements shall be of at least one\nyear\u2019s duration.\u201d\nNew York Idleness\nBelow Expectations\nALBANY, N. Y.\u2014Unemploy\nment in the key industrial state\nof New York was \u201cwell below\nwhat everyone had a right to ex\npect,\u201d and the prospect for next\nyear appeared to be considerably\nbrighter than had been antici\npated, the State Division of Place\nment and Unemployment Insur\nance, State Department of Labor,\nsaid in its annual Analytical report.\nMilton O. Loysen, director of\nthe division, said he expected a\ngradual decline of present unem\nployment levels during the coming\nmonths.\n\u201cWith the settlement of major\ntrikes and a speed-up of indus\ntrial activity,\u201d he report added,\n\u201can absorption of many of the\nunemploymed may be expected in\nthe latter half of 1946. However,\nnew unemployment will arise be\ncause of the continued displace\nment of civilians by veterans, and\n;of women by men. In general,\ni though, a gradual decline during\ni coming months is anticipated in\nunemployment of both veterans\nand non-veterans.\u201d\nCOMMENT ON s\nWORLD NEWS\n(From Labor\u2019s Monthly Survey,\nAmerican Faderation of Labor)\nAn emergency conference of 17\nnations, including representatives\nof United Nations agencies, met\nin London April 3 to consider the\nEuropean wheat and grain criiss.\nIts statements show world wheat,\ngrain and flour requirements of\n19.6 million long tons for the first\nhalf of 1946, with a supply in\nsight of less than 13 million tons,\nleavinga shortage of almost 7\nmillion tons, due largely to war\nravages and droughts.\nThe United States, which is com\nmitted to supply a million tons a\nmonth for 6 months (almost half\nthe 13 million tons available), has\nfallen short by over 10 percent in\nthe first quarter, sending only 2,-\n687,000 tons instead of the pro\nmised 3 million. Government ef\nforts in March prevented a still\ngreater failure and added almost\n300,000 tons to our shipments.\nOf the countries supplying the\nother half, Canada and Australia\nare meeting their commitments;\nArgentina is falling behind because\nan acute fuel shortage makes it\nimpossible to transport her quota.\nEven if all four exporting coun\ntries meet their quotas, world sup\nplies will still be i million tons\nshort.\nTo meet this crisis will require\nthe greatest possible effort on the\npart of all. We in the United States\nmust do our full part, for we have\nthe largest supplies of any coun\ntry. Former President Hoover,\ntouring Europe to study the need,\nreported that of 300 million people\nin Europe west of Russia, only 40\nmillion have assured food supply\ntill the next harvest. Some 22\nmillion children are already devel\noping tuberculosis, rickets and\nother diseases due to undernourish\nment. As the Pope stated April 4:\n\u201cThe shadow of famine rests on at\nleast a quarter of the entire popu\nlation of the globe.\u201d\u2014500,000,000\npeople in Europe and Asia.\nWhat more can we do in USA\nto meet the need? Everyone of us\ncan cooperate in the President\u2019s\nprogram by reducing our consump\ntion of bread and wheat by 40\npercent and of fats by 20 percent.\nFull compliance by everyone could\nsave almost 300,000 tons of wheat\nand rescue 35 million persons from\nstarvation.\nThe government has also cut\nproduction of beer and alcohol to\na minimum to save grain; work\ners affected by this program should\nwork with their unions to devise\nways of supplementing employ\nment during the emergency. Gov\nernment plans to release wheat\nheld on farms are most important.\nAs requested, farmers are raising\nunprecedented numbers of live\nstock this year and reserving wheat\nsupplies more than two million\ntons above normal to feed them.\nA practical plan to release both\ngrain and meat for human food\nwould bring immense help to the\nstarving in Europe and Asia.\n\nEvery possible means of eco\nnomizing and saving w\u2019heat is\nneeded to meet the crisis. Appoint\nment of a food administrator with\npower to secure and ship all avail\nable supplies is the only sure way\nto send the maximum from our\ncountry and get it there on time.\nA world food agency is also needed\nto mobilize world supplies, as an\nnounced by Mr. Hoover April 5.\nWe must recognize that winning\nthe war against starvation, disease\nI and chaos is vital or we shall lose\ni the victory we celebrated on V-J\nDay.\nLabor Men Appointed\nTo N. Y. OP A Boards\nNEW YORK ClTY\u2014Appoint\nment of 5 labor officials to posts\nin price control boards in the New\nYork metropolitan area is an\nnounced by Leo F. Gentner, re\ngional OPA administrator. Among\nthose named were:\nCharles Wysong, or the Rail\nway Clerks Union, as chairman of\nthe Mineola, L. 1., board; Ray\nmond Robertson, of the United\nAssociation of Plumbers, as chair\nman of the Huntington, L. 1.,\nboard.\nWalter Burks, of the Teamsters\nUnion as deputy chairman of the\nManhattan Price Control Board;\nJames Curtin, of the Operating\nEngineers Union, as deputy chair\nman of the Bronx board; Roy\nCollins, of the Railway Conduc\ntors\u2019 Union, as deputy chairman\nof the Staten Island board.\nM\u2019ALLISTER FLORIST\nflowers\nFor All Occasions\nPhone 3-3773\nm g. W. FIBST BTBKET\nTHE PHILBRICK\nOrganization and\nPersonnel Ara Worthy of\nYour Recommendation\nMIAMI CITIZEN, MIAMI, FLORIDA, MAY 9, 1946\nTruman Slaps CIO Public Employes\u2019 Union\nOn Government Strike Issue Taken by Body\nWASHINGTON, D. C. President Truman cracked down\non a newiy formed CIO union of public employes which claims\nthe right to strike when he declared at a press conference that no\nunion can strike against the Government.\nIf that ever happens, the President warned, the Government\nwould cease to exist.\nHis statement was provoked by a reporter\u2019s question regard\ning the action of the ClO\u2019s new United Public Workers of America\nwhich asserts the right to strike against Federal, State or local\nGovernments. The question was:\n\u201cWill you allow Executive Departments to bargain collective\nly with a union whose constitution permits strikes against the\nGovernment?\u201d\nThe President\u2019s answer was brief but emphatic.\nAFL unions representing Government employes have always\nrenounced any right to strike and their constitutions flatly forbid\nstrikes against the Government. This goes for the unions repre\nsenting various groups of Federal workers and for the American\nFederation of State, County and Municipal Employes.\nThe CIO rival unit is a weak and shaky organization which\ncame into existence only a few weeks ago through an amalgama\ntion of its United Federal Workers and its State and local govern-\nment employes union.\nNewspapers in the nation\u2019s capital have been publishing ex\nposes of the Communist leanings of the union\u2019s leaders which were\nconfirmed by the policies adopted at the organization\u2019s first con\nvention.\nResolutions condemning the foreign policy of the United\nStates and Britain were adopted by the convention but all criti\ncism of Soviet Russia was choked off. Abram Flaxer, president\nof the union and many of its lesser officials, have been branded\nas Communists by Congressional investigating committees.\nGreen Rallies Labor, for Enactment\nOf Senate-Approved Housing Bill\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014 Hailing\nSenate passage of the Wagner-\nEllneder-Taft General Housing bill,\nS. 1592 with the AFL-sponsored\nprevailing wage provisions, AFL\nPresident William Green, in a let\nter to all State Federations of La\nbor and Central Labor Unions,\nissued a call for a nationwide drive\nfor House approval of this measure\nwithout weakening amendments.\nCiting powerful forces at work\nagainst the bill, Mr. Green said in\nhis letter:\n\u201cWe have won the first step\nin the fight for a decent home for\nevery American family. The Sen\nate, on April 15, passed the Wag\nner-Ellender-Taft General Housing\nBill, S. 1592. The Senate not only\npassed this measure with all its\nvital provisions intact, but also\nadopted by an overwhelming vote\nof 51 to 20 the AFL-sponsored\nand supported amendment requir\ning that not less than prevailing\nwages be paid on all FHA-insured\nhousing construction.\n\u201cThe Senate adopted this amend\nment to protect the living and\nworking conditions of workers des\npite the powerful organized oppo\nsition.\n\u201cWe now face the second and\nmuch harder fight. This is the fight\nfor passage of this bill by the\nHouse, in the same form it was\npassed by the Senate. The oppon\nents of S. 1592 have been plan\nning their attack on the House\nfrom the day that it was intro\nduced.\n\u201cThe lines of- opposition are\nclear. The major attacks will be\nagainst the prevailing wage amend\nment; against public housing;\nagainst the improvements in our\nTextile Workers\u2019 Convention Raps\nFlood of Anti-Labor Legislation\nWASHINGTON, D. C.\u2014 Strong\ncondemnation of the flood of anti\nlabor legislation pending in Con\ngress was registered by the United\nTextile Workers (AFL) at their\nconvention here.\nResolutions adopted at the ses\nsion called for continuance of the\nOPA, urged unions in each state to\ndemand \u201ccash sickness benefit\u201d.\nlegislation such as that in Rhode\nIsland, supported the United Mine\nWorkers\u2019 strike, backed the pro\njected loan to Britain and directed\nthe international officers to set up\na full research and information\nbureau.\nEarlier the convention rejected,\n196 to 113, proposals to change\nthe union constitution by reduc\ning the number of vice presidents\nfrom seven to two.\nFrank Fenton, AFL national or\nganization director, outlined to the\nconvention the plans for an inten\nsive drive to organize the textile\nworkers throughout the South. He\nexplained he is preparing to use\n\u201ca tremendous number of organiz\ners\u2014southern organizers who un\nderstand the social, economic and\nreligious background of the South.\nWe are going down there because\nwe believe it is time we met cour\nageously the challenge of totali\ntarian, Communist propaganda.\u201d\nChairman I. M. Omburn of the\nAFL Union Label Trades depart\nment, advised the delegates that\n\u201cnow is the time for workers in the\ntextile industry to get something\nfor themselves. The industry now\ncannot meet consumer demands,\nmerchants up and down the street\nare crying for textile goods. When\nsupply can\u2019t meet demand, let\u2019s get\nwages and working conditions com\nmensurate with services rendered.\u201d\nAnthony Valente was reelected\npresident and Lloyd Klenert, sec\nretary-treasurer. The seven vice\npresidents elected are C. E. Earn\nhardt, James E. Carlen, Frank\nSgamboto, Francis Schaufencil,\nEdward Hirschberger, Nick Collins\nand W. R. Herrod.\nFHA system bringing privately\nbuilt homes within the financial\nreach of families with small in\ncomes and otherwise protecting\nhome-buyers.\n\u201cIt is essential that the AFL\nand all its affiliated organizations\nthrow their full weight into the\nfight for immediate passage by the\nHouse for immediate passage by\nthe House of S. 1592 in the same\nform it was passed by the Senate.\nWe must first secure quick and\nfavorable approval by the House\nBanking and Currency committee.\nThe lengthy hearings held by the\nSenate, and the bipartisan spon\nsorship of the bill, make additional,\ndrawn-out hearings unnecessary.\nThen we must fight for prompt\npassage by the House of this bill\nas approved by the Senate, without\namendments.\n\u201cI call upon every organization\naffiliated with the AFL and every\ntrade unionist to act at once to\nhelp secure quick action by the\nHouse on S. 1592 in the Senate\napproved form. A concerted cam\npaign of letters to your Congress\nmen, of strong resolutions by all\nour organizations, of encourag\ning local government and citizens\ngroups to endorse the Senate-ap\nproved bill is your urgent respon\nsibility.\n\u201cIf the House fails to act on\nthis measure during this session,\nor weakens it by amendments, the\nopportunity to enact a comprehen\nsive, labor sponsored Postwar\nHousing Bill will be forever lost.\nThat will be a calamity to all labor.\nWe cannot allow Congress to fail\nus in this hour of greatest housing\nneed. Every union and every union\nmember must help to make his\nCongressman act now.\u201d\nMiami Colonial Hotel\nEngages the Services\nOf Famed Swiss Chef\nThe Miami Colonial hotel has\nengaged the services of William\nB. Benedict, famed chef from Lu\ncerne, Switzerland, to improve its\ndining room service. Benedict for\nmerly was with the New York\nRitz-Carlton Hotel as chief chef.\nThe famed chef is a naturalized\nAmerican. He came to this coun\ntry from Lucerne in 1914 and for\nmerly was head chef at such inter\nnationally famous hotels as the\nGrand in Vienna and The Gelben\nin Budapest. He has been a chef\n33 years, following in the foot\nsteps of his father, who followed\nthat line for 65 years.\nCooking, says Benedict, is the\nworld\u2019s foremost art, because\n\u201cpeople must eat and more men\nand women, therefore, are engaged\nin cooking than in any other art.\u201d\nUnder Benedict\u2019s supervision,\nsays Manager Walter Chandler\nof the Miami Colonial, a smorgas\nbord soon is to be established. To\nbe properly equipped, Benedict\nadds, a smorgasbord must contain\n45 items of food.\nBOILER MAKERS DRAFT\nPLANS FOR ORGANIZING\nKANSAS CITY, Kan. In\ntensive organizing drives are to\nbe inaugurated soon as the result\nof plans drafted at the recent\nBoilermakers\u2019 (AFL) International\nConference in Denver, the broth\nerhood announced.\nThese campaigns are to be\npressed vigorously in all branches\niof the boilermakers\u2019 trade, with\nspecial attention to areas not\npreviously thoroughly organized.\nPlans also were made to build a\nstronger organization in shipyards,\nnavy yards, railroads, petroleum\nindustry, contract shops and other\nfields.\nCOMMITTEE RECOMMENDS\nUSES RETURN TO STATES\nWASHINGTON, D. C. The\nSenate Committee on Education\nand Labor has approved a com\npromise bill which would return\nthe United States Employment\nService to the 48 states, three\nterritories and the District of\nColumbia, as of December 31,\n1946.\nPresident Truman had sought\nto keep federal control of the\nservice until June 30, 1947.\nIn submitting its report, the\nco'mmittee warned against too\nquick dismantling of the various\nUSES offices during the recon\nversion period.\nHazards of Two\nCauseway Curves\nBeing Remedied\nA series of accidents at the two\ncurves on that portion of the\nMacArthur causeway within the\ncity of Miami has been the occa\nsion for some new traffic engineer\ning treatment. Following a recent\naccident on the south curve, ad\njacent to Chalk\u2019s Flying Service,\nstudies were made of the critical\nspeeds at both this curve and the\none farther north, adjacent to the\nBond Boat company.\nMeasurements and computations\nshowed the maximum speed at\nwhich a vehicle can round the\nsouth curve with any assurance of\nsafety to be 30 miles per hour,\naccording to the City Traffic En\ngineering division. The north curve\non the other hand is sharper and\nthe corresponding speed there is\nle>ss\u20142s miles per hour.\nSince 30 miles per hour is the\nlegal speed limit on the Cause\nway, the Traffic Engineering divi\nsion has not considered it desirable\nto post any special speed signs at\nthe south curve. It does point\nout, however, that strict conform\nance with the speed limit which is\nconspicuously posted along this\nstreet is imperative for safety.\nTo enable drivers to see the road\nahead more clearly each of the\nroadways has been divided into\nthree lanes by pavement markings.\nIn the approaches to the north\ncurve where a reduction below the\nspeed limit is necessary for safety,\nsigns reading \u201cSlow to 25 Miles\u201d\nhave been installed in additino to\nthe painting of the lane lines.\nThe purpose of this special re\nstriction, according to the Traffic\nEngineering division, is to help\ndrivers to conform with the legal\nrequirements that no person shall\ndrive \u201cat a speed greater than\nthat which is reasonable and pru\ndent under the conditions then and\nthere existing,\u201d as stated in the\ntraffic ordinance of the city of\nMiami. It serves to inform each\ndriver who approaches the sign\nthat a careful study of the condi\ntions has shown that 25 miles per\nhour is the maximum speed that\ncan be considered \u201creasonable and\nprudent\u201d there.\nThis treatment of conditions at\nthese curves has the approval of\nthe Florida State Highway depart\nment and the Dade County Road\ndepartment, according to the Traf\nfic Engineering division.\nBRITISH UNION, EMPLOYERS\nCELEBRATE AGREEMENT\nWASHINGTON, D. C. Sign\ning of the first national agreement\nfor the furniture manufacturing\ntrade in Britain was marked by\nunusually cordial exchanges be\ntween employers and workers, as\nreported in British newspapers.\nThe unions presented fountain\npens to the members of the em\nployers\u2019 side of the Joint Indus\ntrial Council. The agreement was\nprinted in a little booklet with\ngilt lettering on a bright blue bind\ning.\nFollowing the signing the unions\nentertained the employers at a\nluncheon\u2014a return for a similar\ngesture on the part of the employ\ners some time ago. There were\nmany expressions by both sides of\nmutual confidence and belief in the\nharmonious future of the industry.\nThe United States is shipping\nabout 30 million pounds of vege\ntable seeds to 37 other nations this\nyear\u2014to help hungry people feed\nthemselves.\nSKAGSETH\nStationery Co., Inc.\n53 N. E. First St.\u2014Ph. 2-M9l\n(Across from Red Crone)\nWhite Belt\nDairy\nServing Greeter Miemi for More\nThen e Querter Century\nMilk and Dairy Products from\nOur Own Certified Govern\nment Tested Herd.\nMIAMI. FLA. DIAL 7-2411\nLBQAL XOTICH\nNOTICE\nNOTICE IS HEREBY GIVEN that pur\nsuant to Chapter 194. Florida Statutes.\n1941. the following described land in Dade\nCounty. Florida, will be offered for sale\nat public outcry for the highest and best\ncash bid. at the Court House, beginning\nthe Hour of 11:00 o'clock A. M on the\n31st day of May, 1946.\nDESCRIPTION\nWH of SEM of NWM of SW^ in Sec\ntion 8 Township 52 South. Range 42 East\ncontaining 5 Acres More or Less.\nLot 1 Block 8. Central Miami I*art No.\n1, A Sub. in Section 13. Township 54 South,\nRange 40 East. According to Plat Book\n10 at Page 15.\nLot 22 Block 8. Central Miami Part No.\n1. A Sub. in Section 13. Township 54\nSouth. Range 40 East. According to Piat\nBook 10 at Page 75.\nLots 13 and 14 Block 0. Central Miami\nPart No. 1. A Sub. in Section 13. Town\nship 54 South. Range 40 East. According\nto Plat Book 10 at Page 75.\nLot 23 Block 16 Central Miami Part No.\n1, A Sub. In Section 13. Township 54\nSouth. Range 40 East. According to Plat\nBook 10 at I*nge 75.\nLot 22 Block 17 Central Miami Part No.\nI, A Sub. in Section 13. Township 54\nSouth, Range 40 East. According to Plat\nBook 10 at Page 75.\nLot 27 Block 21 Central Miami Pan No.\n1. A Sub. in Section 13. Township 54\nSouth, Range 40 East. According to Plat\nBook 10 at Page 75.\nLot 3 Block 3. McKeever Terrace. No.\n2. A Sub. in Section 13. Township .\">4 South.\nRange 40 East. According to Plat Book 9\nat Page 123.\nLot 7 Block 3, McKeever Terrace, No. 2.\nA Sub. in Section 13. Township 54 South.\nRange 40 East. According to Plat Book 9\nat Page 123.\nLot 16 Block 3. McKeever Terrace. No. 2,\nA Sub. in Section 13. Township 54 South.\nRange 40 East. According to Plat Book 9\nat Page 123.\nLot 17 Block 3. McKeever Terrace, No. 2.\nA Sub. in Section 13. Township 54 South.\nRange 40 East. According to Plat Book 9\nat Page 123.\nla>t 4 Block 27. Central Miami Part No.\n2. A Sub. In Section 13. Township 54 South,\nRange 40 East. According to Plat Book 10\n\u2022V Page 66.\nLot 2 Block 36. Central Miami Part No\n2. A Sub. is Section 13. Township 71 South.\nRange 40 East. According to Plat Book\n10 at I\u2019age 66.\nIx\u00bbts 1 and 2 Block 45, Amended Plat of\nCetnral Miami I*art No. 3, Commercial\nSection. A Sub. In Section 14. Township\n54 South. Range 40 East. According to\nPlat Book 25 at page 42.\nLots 40 to 42 Block 45. Amended Plat\nof Central Miami Part No. 3. Commercial\nSection, A Sub. in Section 14. Township\n54 South, Range 40 East. According to\nPlat Book 25 at Page 42.\nLot 6 Block 53. Amended Plat of Central\nMARGARET ANN\nNEW\nLLStCHIUINg fl\nBUILDERS SUPPLIES\n3460 N. W. N. River Drive Pheo* 0-2406\nSERVING GRADh\nGREATER \u201cA\"\nMIAMI W PRODUCTS\nCHILDREN NEED\nHomogenized Vitamin \u2018D\u2019 Milk\nArt Cement Manufacturing Co.\n3180 9. W. Sixtee*th Street, Miami 34, Fla.\nP. O. Box 6173, Coral Gable*. Fla.\nRoy Singletary Since 1910\nThe Original ARTCO Lumi-Tai Paste\nArt Cement Paint Coldwater Paint 1 Hour Drying Non-\nThe Permanent Paint for Interior Y allowing Paint\nfor Cement Surf acee Decorating in 10 Paa tel Shade*\nMAY BE PURCHASED FROM YOUR LOCAL DEALER\nIT PAYS TO PAY THE\n400 NORTH MIAMI AVENUE\nHOARDS\nYour Friendly Department Store\nF\nf/\nE MOTHERS\nJrS\nJEW DAY r\nM 11\nAA e\nAnd Richards Is Gift Headquarters\nFor Mothers of All Ages\nMiami Part No. 3. Commercial Saction\nA Sub. in Section 14. Township 54 South\nRange 40 East. According to Plat Book\n25 at Page 42.\nLots 38 and 37 Block 73. Amended Piat\nof Central Miami Part No. 3. Commercial\nSection. A Sub. in Section 14. Township 54\nSouth. Range 40 East. According to Plat\nBook 25 at Page 42.\nLota 22 and 23 Block 74. Amended Flat\nof Central Miami Part No. 3. Commercial\nSection. A Bub. in Section 14. Township\n54 South. Range 40 East. According to\nPlat Book 25 at Page 42.\nLot 7 Block 56. Central Miami Part No.\n4. Amended. A Sub. in Section 14. Town\nship 54 South. Range 40 East. According\nto Plat Book 25 at Page 43\nLot 8 Block 57 Central Miami Part 4.\nAmended A Sub. in Section 14. Township\n54 South, Range 40 East According to\nPlat Book 25 at Page 43\nLots 7 and 8 Block 58. Central Miami\nPart No. 4. Amended A Sub in Section 14.\nTownship 54 South. Range 40 East A.\ncording to Plat 25 at Page 43\nLots 5 and 6 Block 60 Central Miami\nPart No 4. Amended. A Sub in Section\n14. Township 54 South Range 40 East\nAccording to Plat Book 25 at Page 4\nlaits 19 and 20 Block 61 Central Miami\nPart No. 4. Amended A Sub, in Section\n14. Tow nship 54 South. Range 40 East Ac\ncording to Plat Book 2* at Page 43\nLot 9 Block 96. Coral Guides Country\nClub Section Part 5, Amended A Sub in\nSection 19. Township 54 South Range 41\nEast According to Plat Book 23 al\nPage 55.\nla\u00bbt 10 Block .96 Coral Gables Country\nClub Section Part 5. Amended A Sub In\nSection 19. Township 54 South. Range 41\nEast. According to Plat Book 23 at\nPage 55.\nE B LEATHERMAN\nClerk of the Circuit Court\nItade County Florida\n(Circuit Court Seal)\nBy: R M I.EHPER\nDeputy Clerk\n5/9-16\nA good hotel\nin a good town\nThe Parkway\nin\nVero Beach\nOn U. S. Highway No. I\nCommercial Rates\nYear Around\nERA MARKETS\n11","height":"27882","width":"21540"}}
